\emspace  6. Data Model & Persistence 6.1 Proto Schema Organization All data models are defined using Protocol Buffers (proto3) and organized by domain with a consistent structure: proto/insuretech/ \f3\u9500?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  authn/ Authentication Domain \f3\u9474?\f0  \f3\u9500?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  entity/v1/ Data entities \f3\u9474?\f0  \f3\u9474?\f0  \f3\u9500?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  user.proto \f3\u9474?\f0  \f3\u9474?\f0  \f3\u9492?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  session.proto \f3\u9474?\f0  \f3\u9500?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  events/v1/ Domain events \f3\u9474?\f0  \f3\u9474?\f0  \f3\u9492?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  auth_events.proto \f3\u9474?\f0  \f3\u9492?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  services/v1/ gRPC services \f3\u9474?\f0  \f3\u9492?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  auth_service.proto \f3\u9474?\f0  \f3\u9500?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  authz/ Authorization Domain \f3\u9474?\f0  \f3\u9500?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  entity/v1/ \f3\u9474?\f0  \f3\u9500?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  events/v1/ \f3\u9474?\f0  \f3\u9492?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  services/v1/ \f3\u9474?\f0  \f3\u9500?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  policy/ Policy Management Domain \f3\u9474?\f0  \f3\u9500?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  entity/v1/ \f3\u9474?\f0  \f3\u9474?\f0  \f3\u9492?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  policy.proto \f3\u9474?\f0  \f3\u9500?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  events/v1/ \f3\u9474?\f0  \f3\u9492?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  services/v1/ \f3\u9474?\f0  \f3\u9500?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  claims/ Claims Processing Domain \f3\u9474?\f0  \f3\u9500?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  entity/v1/ \f3\u9474?\f0  \f3\u9474?\f0  \f3\u9492?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  claim.proto \f3\u9474?\f0  \f3\u9500?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  events/v1/ \f3\u9474?\f0  \f3\u9492?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  services/v1/ \f3\u9474?\f0  \f3\u9500?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  payment/ Payment Processing Domain \f3\u9474?\f0  \f3\u9500?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  entity/v1/ \f3\u9474?\f0  \f3\u9474?\f0  \f3\u9492?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  payment.proto \f3\u9474?\f0  \f3\u9500?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  events/v1/ \f3\u9474?\f0  \f3\u9492?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  services/v1/ \f3\u9474?\f0  \f3\u9500?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  partner/ Partner Management Domain \f3\u9474?\f0  \f3\u9500?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  entity/v1/ \f3\u9474?\f0  \f3\u9474?\f0  \f3\u9492?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  partner.proto \f3\u9474?\f0  \f3\u9500?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  events/v1/ \f3\u9474?\f0  \f3\u9492?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  services/v1/ \f3\u9474?\f0  \f3\u9500?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  products/ Product Catalog Domain \f3\u9474?\f0  \f3\u9500?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  entity/v1/ \f3\u9474?\f0  \f3\u9500?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  events/v1/ \f3\u9474?\f0  \f3\u9492?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  services/v1/ \f3\u9474?\f0  \f3\u9500?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  notification/ Notification Domain \f3\u9474?\f0  \f3\u9500?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  entity/v1/ \f3\u9474?\f0  \f3\u9500?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  events/v1/ \f3\u9474?\f0  \f3\u9492?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  services/v1/ \f3\u9474?\f0  \f3\u9500?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  ai/ AI Engine Domain \f3\u9474?\f0  \f3\u9500?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  entity/v1/ \f3\u9474?\f0  \f3\u9500?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  events/v1/ \f3\u9474?\f0  \f3\u9492?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  services/v1/ \f3\u9474?\f0  \f3\u9500?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  analytics/ Analytics & BI Domain \f3\u9474?\f0  \f3\u9500?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  entity/v1/ \f3\u9474?\f0  \f3\u9500?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  events/v1/ \f3\u9474?\f0  \f3\u9492?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  services/v1/ \f3\u9474?\f0  \f3\u9492?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  iot/ IoT Integration Domain \f3\u9500?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  entity/v1/ \f3\u9500?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  events/v1/ \f3\u9492?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  services/v1/ See Appendix A for complete proto definitions with code examples. 6.2 Data Architecture Overview The LabAid InsureTech Platform uses a hybrid data architecture combining Protocol Buffers for service contracts with optimized database schemas for persistence: Data Storage Strategy: \f3\u9679?\f0  PostgreSQL 17+: Primary transactional data (policies, claims, users, KYC) \f3\u9679?\f0  TimescaleDB: Time-series data (IoT telemetry, audit logs, analytics) \f3\u9679?\f0  TigerBeetle: Financial transactions with double-entry bookkeeping \f3\u9679?\f0  DynamoDB: Product catalog, configuration, session data \f3\u9679?\f0  Redis 7.0+: Caching, session management, real-time data \f3\u9679?\f0  AWS S3: Document storage (policy certificates, claims documents, images) \f3\u9679?\f0  Apache Kafka: Event streaming and audit logs \f3\u9679?\f0  Pgvector: Vector embeddings for AI/ML operations 6.3 Domain Models 6.3.1 Core Entities Authentication Domain: \f3\u9679?\f0  User - Registered users with mobile/email \f3\u9679?\f0  Session - Active user sessions with JWT tokens \f3\u9679?\f0  OTP - One-time passwords for verification Policy Domain: \f3\u9679?\f0  Policy - Insurance policies with coverage details \f3\u9679?\f0  Applicant - Policyholder information \f3\u9679?\f0  Nominee - Beneficiaries with share percentages \f3\u9679?\f0  Rider - Additional coverage options Claims Domain: \f3\u9679?\f0  Claim - Claim submissions with status tracking \f3\u9679?\f0  ClaimDocument - Supporting documents (bills, reports) \f3\u9679?\f0  ClaimApproval - Multi-level approval workflow \f3\u9679?\f0  FraudCheck - Fraud detection results Payment Domain: \f3\u9679?\f0  Payment - Financial transactions \f3\u9679?\f0  Transaction - Double-entry accounting records \f3\u9679?\f0  Refund - Refund processing Partner Domain: \f3\u9679?\f0  Partner - Business partners (hospitals, MFS, e-commerce) \f3\u9679?\f0  Agent - Sales representatives \f3\u9679?\f0  Commission - Commission structure and calculations 6.4 Proto-First Data Model Strategy 6.4.1 Why Proto-First? Single Source of Truth: The LabAid InsureTech Platform adopts a Proto-First approach where Protocol Buffer definitions serve as the canonical data model across all layers: Proto Definitions (Source of Truth) \f3\u9500?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  Code Generation \f4\u8594?\f0  Go/C#/Python/Node.js structs \f3\u9500?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  Database Schema \f4\u8594?\f0  PostgreSQL/TimescaleDB tables \f3\u9500?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  API Contracts \f4\u8594?\f0  gRPC/REST endpoints \f3\u9500?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  Event Schemas \f4\u8594?\f0  Kafka message formats \f3\u9492?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  Documentation \f4\u8594?\f0  Auto-generated API docs Key Benefits: \f3\u9679?\f0  \f3\u9989?\f0  Type Safety: Compile-time validation across all services \f3\u9679?\f0  \f3\u9989?\f0  Consistency: Same data structure in app, database, and APIs \f3\u9679?\f0  \f3\u9989?\f0  Versioning: Built-in support for backward/forward compatibility \f3\u9679?\f0  \f3\u9989?\f0  Multi-Language: Generate code for Go, C#, Python, Node.js from single source \f3\u9679?\f0  \f3\u9989?\f0  Performance: Efficient binary serialization with Protocol Buffers \f3\u9679?\f0  \f3\u9989?\f0  Documentation: Self-documenting with comments in proto files\par
6.4.2 Schema Generation Workflow Step 1: Define Proto Schemas // proto/insuretech/policy/entity/v1/policy.proto message Policy \{ string policy_id = 1; // UUID string policy_number = 2; // LBT-YYYY-XXXX-NNNNNN string customer_id = 3; PolicyStatus status = 4; double premium_amount = 5; google.protobuf.Timestamp created_at = 6; \} Step 2: Generate Database Schema\par
Using buf or protoc-gen-sql\par
buf generate\par
Outputs: migrations/001_initial_schema.sql\par
CREATE TABLE policies ( policy_id UUID PRIMARY KEY, policy_number VARCHAR(50) UNIQUE NOT NULL, customer_id UUID NOT NULL, status VARCHAR(50) NOT NULL, premium_amount DECIMAL(12,2) NOT NULL, created_at TIMESTAMP NOT NULL ); Step 3: Manual Optimization (Enhancement Layer) -- migrations/002_add_indexes.sql CREATE INDEX idx_policies_customer_id ON policies(customer_id); CREATE INDEX idx_policies_status ON policies(status); CREATE INDEX idx_policies_created_at ON policies(created_at DESC);\par
-- Add foreign keys ALTER TABLE policies ADD CONSTRAINT fk_customer FOREIGN KEY (customer_id) REFERENCES users(user_id);\par
-- Add constraints ALTER TABLE policies ADD CONSTRAINT chk_premium_positive CHECK (premium_amount > 0); Step 4: Generate Application Code\par
Go\par
protoc --go_out=. --go-grpc_out=. proto/**/*.proto\par
C#\par
protoc --csharp_out=. --grpc_out=. proto/**/*.proto\par
Python\par
python -m grpc_tools.protoc -I. --python_out=. --grpc_python_out=. proto/**/.proto6.4.3 Database Strategy by TypePostgreSQL (Primary Transactional Database)Generated Tables:From proto/insuretech/authn/entity/v1/.proto: \f3\u9500?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  users (User proto \f4\u8594?\f0  users table) \f3\u9500?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  user_profiles (UserProfile proto) \f3\u9500?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  sessions (Session proto) \f3\u9492?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  otps (OTP proto)\par
From proto/insuretech/policy/entity/v1/*.proto: \f3\u9500?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  policies (Policy proto) \f3\u9500?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  policy_nominees (Nominee proto) \f3\u9492?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  policy_riders (Rider proto)\par
From proto/insuretech/claims/entity/v1/*.proto: \f3\u9500?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  claims (Claim proto) \f3\u9500?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  claim_documents (ClaimDocument proto) \f3\u9500?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  claim_approvals (ClaimApproval proto) \f3\u9492?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  fraud_checks (FraudCheckResult proto)\par
From proto/insuretech/payment/entity/v1/*.proto: \f3\u9492?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  payments (Payment proto)\par
From proto/insuretech/partner/entity/v1/*.proto: \f3\u9500?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  partners (Partner proto) \f3\u9492?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  agents (Agent proto) Enhancement Strategy: \f3\u9679?\f0  Indexes: Add for frequently queried columns (customer_id, status, dates) \f3\u9679?\f0  Foreign Keys: Enforce referential integrity \f3\u9679?\f0  Constraints: Business rules (amount > 0, dates logical) \f3\u9679?\f0  Triggers: Audit logging, automatic timestamp updates \f3\u9679?\f0  Partitioning: For large tables (policies by year, claims by month) TimescaleDB (Time-Series Database) Generated Hypertables: From proto/insuretech/iot/entity/v1/device.proto: \f3\u9492?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  telemetry (Telemetry proto \f4\u8594?\f0  hypertable on timestamp)\par
From proto/insuretech/authn/events/v1/*.proto: \f3\u9492?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  audit_logs (Event protos \f4\u8594?\f0  hypertable)\par
From proto/insuretech/analytics/entity/v1/*.proto: \f3\u9492?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  metrics (Metric proto \f4\u8594?\f0  hypertable) Enhancement Strategy: -- Create hypertable SELECT create_hypertable('telemetry', 'timestamp');\par
-- Add continuous aggregates for dashboards CREATE MATERIALIZED VIEW telemetry_hourly WITH (timescaledb.continuous) AS SELECT time_bucket('1 hour', timestamp) AS hour, device_id, AVG(metrics->>'speed') as avg_speed, COUNT(*) as data_points FROM telemetry GROUP BY hour, device_id;\par
-- Set retention policy (90 days hot, archive rest) SELECT add_retention_policy('telemetry', INTERVAL '90 days'); DynamoDB (NoSQL Document Store) Generated Collections: From proto/insuretech/products/entity/v1/product.proto: \f3\u9492?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  products_catalog (Product proto \f4\u8594?\f0  DynamoDB items)\par
From proto/insuretech/authn/entity/v1/session.proto: \f3\u9492?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  active_sessions (Session proto \f4\u8594?\f0  TTL-enabled items) Key Design: \f3\u9679?\f0  Primary Key: entity_id (from proto) \f3\u9679?\f0  Sort Key: timestamp or type (from proto fields) \f3\u9679?\f0  TTL: For session data (expires_at from proto) \f3\u9679?\f0  Global Secondary Indexes: Based on query patterns TigerBeetle (Financial Ledger) Generated Accounts: From proto/insuretech/payment/entity/v1/payment.proto: Account types mapped from PaymentType enum: \f3\u9500?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  Premium Collection Accounts \f3\u9500?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  Claims Settlement Accounts \f3\u9500?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  Commission Payment Accounts \f3\u9492?\u9472?\u9472?\f0  Refund Accounts Double-Entry Example: Premium Payment (BDT 1,500): Debit: Customer Account -1,500 BDT Credit: Premium Collection +1,500 BDT 6.4.4 Migration Strategy Phase 1: Initial Schema Generation\par
Generate from all entity protos\par
protoc-gen-sql --out=migrations/001_initial_schema.sql proto/insuretech//entity/v1/.proto\par
Apply to database\par
psql -d insuretech_dev -f migrations/001_initial_schema.sql Phase 2: Add Enhancements -- migrations/002_add_indexes.sql CREATE INDEX CONCURRENTLY idx_policies_customer_status ON policies(customer_id, status);\par
-- migrations/003_add_foreign_keys.sql ALTER TABLE policies ADD CONSTRAINT fk_customer ...; ALTER TABLE claims ADD CONSTRAINT fk_policy ...;\par
-- migrations/004_add_partitioning.sql CREATE TABLE policies_2025 PARTITION OF policies FOR VALUES FROM ('2025-01-01') TO ('2026-01-01'); Phase 3: Data Migration -- migrations/005_migrate_legacy_data.sql INSERT INTO users (user_id, mobile_number, ...) SELECT uuid_generate_v4(), phone, ... FROM legacy_customers; Phase 4: Performance Optimization -- migrations/006_optimize_queries.sql CREATE MATERIALIZED VIEW policy_summary AS SELECT customer_id, COUNT(*) as policy_count, SUM(premium_amount) as total_premium FROM policies WHERE status = 'ACTIVE' GROUP BY customer_id;\par
-- Refresh strategy REFRESH MATERIALIZED VIEW CONCURRENTLY policy_summary; 6.4.5 Schema Versioning Strategy Proto Evolution: // v1 - Initial version message Policy \{ string policy_id = 1; double premium_amount = 2; \}\par
// v2 - Add new field (backward compatible) message Policy \{ string policy_id = 1; double premium_amount = 2; string partner_id = 3; // New field - optional by default \}\par
// v3 - Deprecate field (forward compatible) message Policy \{ string policy_id = 1; double premium_amount = 2; string partner_id = 3; double old_field = 4 [deprecated = true]; // Mark as deprecated \} Database Migration for Proto Changes: -- When adding field to proto ALTER TABLE policies ADD COLUMN partner_id UUID;\par
-- When deprecating field -- Keep column for backward compatibility, mark in comments COMMENT ON COLUMN policies.old_field IS 'DEPRECATED: Use new_field instead';\par
-- After grace period, drop column ALTER TABLE policies DROP COLUMN old_field; 6.4.6 Data Consistency Patterns Strong Consistency (PostgreSQL) Policy Creation:\par
Begin Transaction\par
Insert into policies\par
Insert into policy_nominees\par
Insert into policy_riders\par
Commit (all or nothing) Eventual Consistency (Event-Driven) Policy Issued Event \f4\u8594?\f0  Kafka: \f3\u9500?\f4\u8594?\f0  Notification Service (send SMS) \f3\u9500?\f4\u8594?\f0  Analytics Service (update metrics) \f3\u9500?\f4\u8594?\f0  Partner Service (calculate commission) \f3\u9492?\f4\u8594?\f0  Document Service (generate PDF)\par
Each service processes independently with retries CQRS Pattern Command (Write): Proto \f4\u8594?\f0  Service Logic \f4\u8594?\f0  PostgreSQL (write) \f4\u8594?\f0  Kafka Event\par
Query (Read): Proto \f4\u8594?\f0  Read Model (materialized view) \f4\u8594?\f0  Fast response 7.4.7 Backup and Recovery PostgreSQL Backup:\par
Daily full backup\par
pg_dump insuretech_prod > backup_$(date +%Y%m%d).sql\par
Point-in-time recovery (WAL archiving)\par
archive_command = 'cp %p /archive/%f'\par
Proto Schema Backup:\par
Proto files are version controlled in Git\par
git tag v3.7-schemas git push origin v3.7-schemas\par
Can regenerate schemas from any tagged version\par
git checkout v3.7-schemas buf generate\par
6.5 Data Migration Strategy Proto-to-Database Mapping: \f3\u9679?\f0  Proto definitions serve as canonical data models \f3\u9679?\f0  Database schemas generated from proto files \f3\u9679?\f0  Migrations managed via version-controlled SQL scripts \f3\u9679?\f0  Backward compatibility maintained through proto versioning Migration Phases: \f3\u9679?\f0  Phase 1: Core entities (User, Policy, Claim, Payment) \f3\u9679?\f0  Phase 2: Extended entities (Partner, Agent, Product) \f3\u9679?\f0  Phase 3: Advanced features (IoT, AI, Analytics) 6.6 CQRS Implementation Command Side (Write): \f3\u9679?\f0  Commands update primary PostgreSQL database \f3\u9679?\f0  Events published to Kafka \f3\u9679?\f0  Strong consistency guarantees Query Side (Read): \f3\u9679?\f0  Materialized views for complex queries \f3\u9679?\f0  Read replicas for reporting \f3\u9679?\f0  Eventual consistency acceptable \f3\u9679?\f0  Cached frequently accessed data in Redis Example Flow: CreatePolicy Command \f4\u8594?\f0  PostgreSQL INSERT \f4\u8594?\f0  Kafka PolicyCreated Event \f4\u8595?\f0  Read Model Update (async) \f4\u8595?\f0  Policy Query \f4\u8594?\f0  Redis Cache \f4\u8594?\f0  Read Replica\par
